<dl id="n12019m"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12019m">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12019m"> 19(m)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ heartscald</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">La religion d&apos;Odin semble avoir &eacute;t&eacute; cr&eacute;&eacute;e par un Scandinave, qui aurait &eacute;t&eacute; initi&eacute; &agrave; la religion de Zoroastre et qui l&apos;aurait appliqu&eacute;e aux moeurs et aux passions d&apos;un peuple barbare, en haine de l&apos;empire romain, et pour pr&eacute;parer ce peuple &agrave; une immense invasion. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Cet Odin Frighe, plus tard divinis&eacute; par les Scaldes et identifi&eacute; avec le Dieu supr&ecirc;me, W&ocirc;dan, fut &eacute;videmment l&apos;organisateur primitif de la religion scandinave et germanique. <br> <font color="green">[The religion of Odin seems to have been created by a Scandinavian who was initiated in the religion of Zoroaster and who applied it to the habits and the passions of a barbarous people, hating the Roman empire, and to prepare this people for an immense invasion. [&hellip;]</font> This Odin Frighe, later made divine by the Scalds and identified with the supreme God Wodan, was evidently the primitive organizer of Scandinavian and Germanic religion.] <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLL"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1892) 168</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
